# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1982-commonwealth-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The **1930 British Empire Games** were the inaugural edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, and was held in Hamilton, Ontario, from 16 to 23 August 1930.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was organized by *Hamilton Spectator* sportswriter Bobby Robinson after he attended the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam as manager of the Canadian track and field team and was inspired to create a similar event for the British Empire.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] After campaigning for the idea among contacts he met at the Olympics, he was asked to organise the first British Empire Games in Hamilton.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Fellow Hamilton journalist Ivan Miller helped with the organizing committee.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The sports included athletics, boxing, lawn bowls, rowing, swimming, and wrestling.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony and athletics events were held at Civic Stadium (later renamed Ivor Wynne Stadium) in east Hamilton.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was opened by the Governor General of Canada, Lord Willingdon, on 16 August.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Canadian triple jumper Gordon Smallacombe claimed the debut gold medal a few hours later.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The 1930 British Empire Games made use of pedestals for dignitaries to present medals to winning athletes, as proposed by Bobby Robinson.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] This inspired the Olympic medal podium ceremonies which began at the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The **1934 British Empire Games** were the second edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, held in England, from 4–11 August 1934.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The host city was London, with the main venues at Wembley Park and the White City Stadium, although the track cycling events were in Manchester.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Seventeen national teams took part, including the Irish Free State (the only Games in which they participated, although an all-Ireland team competed at the 1930 Games).
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The 1934 Games had been originally awarded to Johannesburg, South Africa, but the change of venue to London was made due to concerns regarding the treatment of black and Asian athletes by South African officials and fans.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Six sports were featured in the Games with rowing being dropped from 1930 but cycling making its first appearance.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Athletics took place at the White City Stadium, while boxing, wrestling, and aquatics (swimming and diving) were held at the Wembley Empire Pool, where the swimming pool would be converted overnight into an arena with 7,000 additional seats brought in to increase the capacity to 12,000.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Lawn bowls was held at two clubs in Paddington and Temple, while the cycling was held at the Fallowfield Stadium in Manchester.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Events for women athletes included a debut in athletics; the previous games had women's events in swimming and diving only.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The Wembley Empire Pool was built specifically for the games on the instruction of Arthur Elvin and had been completed in just nine months, opening 10 days before the start of the Games on 25 July.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] (Teams participating for the first time in **bold**).
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The **1938 British Empire Games** were the third British Empire Games, the event that evolved to become the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Held in Sydney, Australia, from 5–12 February 1938, they were timed to coincide with Sydney's sesqui-centenary (150 years since the foundation of British settlement in Australia).
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Venues included the Sydney Cricket Ground (the main stadium), the North Sydney Olympic Pool and Henson Park.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] An estimated 40,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] A men's residential village was established within the grounds of the Sydney Showground, while the female athletes were housed in hotels.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The star of the games was the Australian athlete Decima Norman, who won five gold medals in track and field.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Margaret Dovey, later married to Australian prime minister Gough Whitlam, finished sixth in the 220 yards breaststroke.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Due to the onset of World War II, the games were not held again until 1950.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The **1950 British Empire Games** were the fourth staging of what is now called the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] It was held in Auckland, New Zealand, between 4 and 11 February 1950, after a 12-year gap from the third edition of the games due to World War II.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The fourth games were originally awarded to Montreal, Canada and were to be held in 1942 but were cancelled due to the War.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The Games were declared open by Sir Bernard Freyberg.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony was held at Eden Park and was sold out with 40,000 people attending.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Eden Park also served as the main venue, while the closing ceremonies were held at Western Springs Stadium.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Other venues included the Auckland Town Hall and the Newmarket Olympic Pool.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] A 1950 British Empire Games documentary film of the games was made by the New Zealand National Film Unit.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] At the 1950 British Empire Games all the teams won at least one medal.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Vancouver, British Columbia, from 30 July to 7 August 1954.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the fifth edition of the event that would eventually become known as the Commonwealth Games, the second post-war Games, the second Canadian Games after the inaugural event in Hamilton and the first event since the name change from British Empire Games took effect in 1952.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Other bids to stage the Games were received from Toronto, Montreal and Hamilton.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The main venue was the Empire Stadium, which had been specifically constructed for the games at the cost of £500,000.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Work on the 25,000 seated stadium started in October 1953 and the keys were handed over to Stan Smith (General chairman of the games) on 12 July 1954.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The games were attended by 24 nations and 662 competitors.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the first time that the games gained a television audience, when CBC and NBC transmitted pictures to an estimated 100 million North American viewers.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Recordings of the games were also shown on the BBC Television Service, beginning a consistent association between the BBC and the Commonwealth Games which only ended in 2026.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was at these games that the "Miracle Mile" took place between Roger Bannister and John Landy at the Empire Stadium.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the first time these two (and at that time the only two) sub-four-minute mile runners appeared in the same race, and also the first time two runners broke four minutes in the same race.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] On the same afternoon, Jim Peters, the holder of the world best time for the marathon, entered the stadium 17 minutes ahead of his nearest rival, but collapsed on his final lap, and never completed the race.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 24 teams were represented at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union won the most gold and overall medals at these Games.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to be staged in the Southern Hemisphere and Oceania, as well as the first to be held outside Europe and North America.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne is the most southerly city ever to host the Olympics.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Australia hosted the Games for a second time in 2000 in Sydney, New South Wales, and will host them again in 2032 in Brisbane, Queensland.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympic equestrian events could not be held in Melbourne due to Australia's strict quarantine regulations, so they were held in Stockholm five months earlier.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] This was the second time the Olympics were not held entirely in one country, the first being the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium, with some events taking place in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Despite uncertainties and various complications encountered during the preparations, the 1956 Games went ahead in Melbourne as planned and turned out to be a success.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Started during the 1956 Games was the "Parade of Athletes" at the closing ceremonies.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Nine teams boycotted the Games for various reasons.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Four teams (Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon) boycotted in response to the Suez Crisis, in which Egypt was invaded by Israel, France and the United Kingdom.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Four teams (the Netherlands, Spain, Liechtenstein and Switzerland) boycotted in response to the Soviet invasion of Hungary, and the People's Republic of China's boycott was in response to a dispute with the Republic of China over the right to represent China.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] One of the most notable events of the games was a controversial water polo match between the Soviet Union and the defending champions, Hungary.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union had recently suppressed an anti-authoritarian revolution in Hungary and violence broke out between the teams during the match, resulting in numerous injuries.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] When Hungary's Ervin Zádor suffered bleeding after being punched by the Soviet Union's Valentin Prokopov, spectators attempted to join the violence, but they were blocked by police.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The match was cancelled, with Hungary being declared the winner because they were in the lead 4–0.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne was selected as the host city over bids from Buenos Aires, Mexico City, Montreal, Los Angeles, Detroit, Chicago, Minneapolis, Philadelphia, and San Francisco at the 43rd IOC Session in Rome, Italy on 28 April 1949.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Mexico City, Montreal and Los Angeles would eventually be selected to host the 1968, 1976 and 1984 Summer Olympics respectively.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Many members of the IOC were skeptical about Melbourne as an appropriate site.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Its location in the Southern Hemisphere was a major concern since the reversal of seasons would mean the Games must be held during the northern winter.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The November–December schedule was thought likely to inconvenience athletes from the Northern Hemisphere, who were accustomed to resting during their winter.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Notwithstanding these concerns, the field of candidates eventually narrowed to two Southern Hemisphere cities, these being Melbourne and Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Melbourne was selected, in 1949, to host the 1956 Olympics by a one-vote margin.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The first sign of trouble was the revelation that Australian equine quarantine would prevent the country from hosting the equestrian events.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Stockholm was selected as the alternative site, so equestrian competition began on 10 June, five and a half months before the rest of the Olympic Games were to open.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The above problems of the Melbourne Games were compounded by bickering over financing among Australian politicians.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Eventually, in March 1953, the State Government accepted a £2 million loan from the Commonwealth Government to build the Olympic Village, which would accommodate up to 6,000 people, in Heidelberg West.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] After the Olympics, the houses in the village were handed back to the Housing Commission for general public housing.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] At one point, IOC President Avery Brundage suggested that Rome, which was to host the 1960 Games, was so far ahead of Melbourne in preparations that it might be ready as a replacement site in 1956.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Constructing of the sporting venues was given priority over the athlete's village.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The village was designed as a whole new suburb with semi-detached houses and flats, the first village that both sexes could cohabitate the same buildings instead of gender designated sections.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] As late as April 1955, Brundage, who was presiding over the Olympics for the first time, was still doubtful about Melbourne and was not satisfied by an inspection trip to the city.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Construction was well under way by then, thanks to a $4.5 million federal loan to Victoria, but it was behind schedule.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] He still held out the possibility that Rome might have to step in.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] By the beginning of 1956, though, it was obvious that Melbourne would be ready for the Olympics.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Egypt, Iraq, Cambodia and Lebanon announced that they would not participate in the Olympics in response to the Suez Crisis when Egypt was invaded by Israel, the United Kingdom, and France.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The Netherlands, Spain, Switzerland and Liechtenstein boycotted the event in protest of the Soviet Union's crushing of the Hungarian Revolution.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The People's Republic of China chose to boycott the event because Taiwan had been allowed to compete.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Athletes from both East and West Germany competed together as a combined team (a display of unity that was repeated in 1960 and 1964, but was then discontinued).
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Although the number of countries participating (67) was almost the same as in 1952 (69), the number of athletes competing dropped sharply, from 4,925 to 3,342.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Once underway, the Games progressed smoothly, and came to be known as the "Friendly Games".
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Betty Cuthbert, an 18-year-old from Sydney, won the 100 and 200 metre sprint races and ran an exceptional final leg in the 4 x 100 metre relay to overcome Great Britain's lead and claim her third gold medal, becoming known as the "Golden Girl".
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The veteran Shirley Strickland repeated her 1952 win in the 80 metre hurdles and was also part of the winning 4 x 100 metre relay team, bringing her career Olympic medal total to seven: three golds, a silver, and three bronze medals.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] They won all of the freestyle races, men's and women's, and collected a total of eight gold, four silver and two bronze medals.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Murray Rose became the first male swimmer to win two freestyle events (and a total three events) since Johnny Weissmuller in 1924, while Dawn Fraser won gold medals in the 100 metre freestyle and as the leadoff swimmer in the 4 x 100 metre relay team.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The men's track and field events were dominated by the United States.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] They not only won 15 of the 24 events, they swept four of them and took first and second place in five others.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Bobby Morrow led the way with gold medals in the 100 and 200 metre sprints and the 4 x 100 metre relay.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Tom Courtney barely overtook Great Britain's Derek Johnson in the 800 metre run, then collapsed from the exertion and needed medical attention.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Ireland's Ronnie Delany ran an outstanding 53.8 over the last 400 metres to win the 1,500 metre run (also Ireland's last gold medal in track events), in which favourite John Landy of Australia finished third.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] There was a major upset, marred briefly by controversy, in the 3,000 metre steeplechase.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Little-known Chris Brasher of Great Britain finished well ahead of the field, but the judges disqualified him for interfering with Norway's Ernst Larsen, and they announced Sándor Rozsnyói of Hungary as the winner.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Brasher's appeal was supported by Larsen, Rozsnyói, and fourth-place finisher Heinz Laufer of Germany.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Subsequently, the decision was reversed and Brasher became the first Briton to win a gold medal in track and field since 1936.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Soviet runner Vladimir Kuts won two golds by winning both the 5,000-metre and 10,000-metre events.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Only two world records were set in track and field.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Mildred McDaniel, the first American woman to win gold in the sport, set a high jump record of 1.76 metres (5.8 ft), and Egil Danielsen of Norway overcame blustery conditions with a remarkable javelin throw of 85.71 metres (281.2 ft).
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Throughout the Olympics, Hungarian athletes were cheered by fans from Australia and other countries.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Many of them gathered in the boxing arena when thirty-year-old Laszlo Papp of Hungary won a record third gold medal by beating José Torres for the light-middleweight championship.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] A few days later, the crowd was with the Hungarian water polo team in its hotly contested and emotionally charged match against the Soviet Union which took place against the background of the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The game became rough and, when a Hungarian was forced to leave the pool with a bleeding wound above his eye, a riot almost broke out.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The police restored order and the game was called early, with Hungary leading 4–0, and the Hungarians went on to win the gold medal.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] In a much publicized Olympic romance, American hammer throw champion Hal Connolly would marry Czechoslovak discus throw champion, Olga Fikotová.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] After moving to the United States, Olga wanted to continue representing Czechoslovakia, but the Czechoslovak Olympic Committee would not allow her to do so.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Thereafter, as Olga Connolly, she took part in every Olympics until 1972 competing for the U.S.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] She was the flag bearer for the U.S. team at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The India men's national field hockey team won its sixth consecutive Olympic gold.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Despite the international tensions of 1956—or perhaps because of them—a young Melburnian, John Ian Wing, came up with a new idea for the closing ceremony.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Instead of marching as separate teams, behind their national flags, the athletes mingled together as they paraded into and around the arena for a final appearance before the spectators.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] It was the start of an Olympic tradition that has been followed ever since.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympic flame was relayed to Melbourne after being lit at Olympia on 2 November 1956.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Greek runners took the flame from Olympia to Athens.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The flame was then transferred to a miner's lamp, flown by a Qantas Super Constellation aircraft, "Southern Horizon" to Darwin, Northern Territory.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] A Royal Australian Air Force English Electric Canberra jet bomber transported the flame to Cairns, Queensland, where it arrived on 9 November 1956 and the Mayor of Cairns, Alderman W.J.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Fulton, lit the first torch with the torch design was identical to the one used for the 1948 London Games (except for the engraved city name and year).
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The first runner was Con Verevis, a local man of Greek parentage.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The flame was relayed down the east coast of Australia using die cast aluminium torches weighing about 3 pounds (1.8 kg).
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The flame arrived in Melbourne on 22 November 1956, the day of the opening ceremony and The flame was lit at the Olympic stadium by Ron Clarke, who accidentally burned his arm in the process.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] While the Olympic flame was being carried to Sydney, an Australian veterinary student named Barry Larkin carried a fake Olympic Flame and fooled the mayor of Sydney.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The Melbourne Olympic Arts Festival was an arts festival held in conjunction with the Olympics.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The Olympics were first televised during the 1936 games to a domestic audience in Berlin.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The 1956 Winter Olympics in Cortina d'Ampezzo were broadcast internationally with the organising committee giving the television rights gratis.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] While there was much interest in the games overseas, no international television or newsreel rights were awarded, as the Melbourne organising committee requested licensing payments for the broadcasting rights.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] However, domestic rights to the games were hastily agreed by the then three Melbourne stations, GTV9, HSV7 and ABV2, only a week before the opening ceremony.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The three Sydney stations, TCN9, ATN7 and ABN2, syndicated the Melbourne coverage.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Television in Australia was new, having its beginnings in September 1956.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] For many Australians, their first glimpse of television were Olympic broadcasts.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Around five thousand television sets were in Australia by the time of the Games, so the domestic audience largely watched the games at community halls and at Ampol petrol stations.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] The 1956 Summer Olympics featured 17 different sports encompassing 23 disciplines, and medals were awarded in 151 events (145 events in Melbourne and 6 equestrian events in Stockholm).
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] A total of 67 nations competed in the 1956 Olympics.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Eight countries made their Olympic debuts: Cambodia (only competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm), Ethiopia, Fiji, Kenya, Liberia, Malaya, North Borneo (modern-day Sabah of Malaysia), and Uganda.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Athletes from East Germany and West Germany competed together as the United Team of Germany, an arrangement that would last until 1968.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] For the first time, the team of Republic of China effectively represented only Taiwan.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Five nations competed in the equestrian events in Stockholm, but did not attend the Games in Melbourne.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Cambodia, Egypt and Lebanon did not compete in Melbourne due to a boycott regarding the Suez Crisis, whilst the Netherlands, Spain and Switzerland all boycotted the Melbourne Olympics in protest at the Soviet invasion of Hungary.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Nations that returned to the games in this edition included Afghanistan and Colombia.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Helsinki 1952 but was absent in Melbourne 1956 included the People's Republic of China, Liechtenstein, Netherlands Antilles, and Saar.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Puerto Rico is an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] Bahamas, Bermuda, Fiji, Gold Coast (modern-day Ghana), Hong Kong, Jamaica, Kenya, Nigeria, Malaya, North Borneo, Singapore, Trinidad and Tobago, Uganda and British Guyana was all part of the British Empire.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1956-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1956 Games.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** (Welsh: *Gemau Ymerodraeth Prydain a'r Gymanwlad* 1958) were held in Cardiff, Wales, from 18 to 26 July 1958.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the sixth edition of what would come to be known as the Commonwealth Games, the second Games held in the United Kingdom, and the second held under the name **British Empire and Commonwealth Games**.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Thirty-five nations sent a total of 1,130 athletes and 228 officials to the Cardiff Games and 23 countries and dependencies won medals, including, for the first time, Singapore, Ghana, Kenya and the Isle of Man.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 178,000 tickets were eventually sold during the Games.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The Cardiff Games introduced the Queen's Baton Relay, which has been conducted as a prelude to every Commonwealth Games ever since.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The British Empire and Commonwealth Games, including the opening and closing ceremonies, were held at the Cardiff Arms Park.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The following venues were used during the Games.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 36 countries and territories were represented (and 1,100 athletes), being the largest number to date, with a significant number of teams competing for the first time at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] At Cardiff Arms Park, an anti-apartheid crowd protested at the all-white South African team; games organisers responded that non-white South Africans were ineligible as their associations were not affiliated to the international federations.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1958-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] South Africa left the Commonwealth in 1961 and next appeared at the Games in 1994.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The **1982 Commonwealth Games** were held in Brisbane, Australia, from 30 September to 9 October 1982.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The Opening Ceremony was held at the QEII Stadium (named after Elizabeth II), in the Brisbane suburb of Nathan.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The QEII Stadium was also the athletics and archery events venue.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Other events were held at the purpose-built Sleeman Sports Complex in Chandler.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The Chairman of the 1982 Commonwealth Games was Sir Edward Williams.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The 1982 Commonwealth Games Logo was designed by Hugh Edwards.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The symbol is derived from the form of a bounding kangaroo.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The three bands, forming stylized A's (for Australia), and is in colours which are common to flags of many Commonwealth countries.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The mascot for the games was also designed by Hugh Edwards and is a caricature of a kangaroo was named Matilda.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] A 13-meter-high (43-foot) mechanical kangaroo travelled around the stadium and winked at the crowd.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The event was officially opened by The Duke of Edinburgh and closed by Elizabeth II.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Bidding for the XII Commonwealth Games was held in Montreal, Canada, at the 1976 Montreal Summer Olympics.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Lagos, Brisbane, Kuala Lumpur, and Birmingham were the bidding cities.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] On 14 July 1976, it was announced that Brisbane had won the rights to stage the Games after the other candidate cities withdrew bids.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Sixteen years after the Brisbane Games, Kuala Lumpur hosted the 1998 Commonwealth Games, while Birmingham hosted the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Brisbane was awarded the Games by default after being the only candidate city left at the bid election after Birmingham reversed its decision to submit an application.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Nigeria's boycott of the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal made Lagos' bid lobbying impractical.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal were plagued with cost overruns, and bidding on a sports festival anywhere in the world was not good politically.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Forty-six Commonwealth nations and territories took part in the 1982 Commonwealth Games.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] A total of 1,583 athletes and 571 officials participated in the event.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The Griffith University student dormitories in the adjoining Nathan Campus were used as athletes' villages.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The ceremony at the QEII Stadium was held on a fine but extremely windy day.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The wind was so strong that skydivers who were going to descend into the stadium were cancelled.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Instead they made an entrance at the closing ceremony.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Elizabeth II closed the Games during a colourful ceremony, which included parachute jumpers (who had originally been also intended as part of the Opening Ceremony display) jumping and landing in a special target area within the stadium and red, white and blue balloons.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Matilda the Kangaroo also winked at the Queen.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Following the closing of the Games, the Queen and the Duke left the stand to be driven from the stadium.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] However, nobody wanted the Games to end and the Australian team formed a 'guard of honour' and ran beside and behind the car in which Queen Elizabeth and Prince Philip were travelling, as it circled the stadium several times before finally leaving.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Team members from other countries also joined in running after the royal car.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Sports contested during the 1982 Commonwealth Games included athletics, archery, badminton, lawn bowls, boxing, cycling, shooting, swimming, diving, weightlifting and wrestling.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Table tennis and Australian rules football were demonstration sports, with the latter being demonstrated at a 6 October rematch at the Gabba of that year's VFL Grand Final, which took place just 11 days before at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Richmond won the demonstration rematch with a score of 28.16 (184) to Carlton's 26.10 (166).
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] This is the full table of the **medal count** of the **1982 Commonwealth Games**.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] These rankings sort by the number of gold medals earned by a country.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The number of silvers is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] If, after the above, countries are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] This follows the system used by the IOC, IAAF and BBC.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The first event of the Games was 100 kilometres (62 mi) Road Trial in cycling.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] England won the Gold Medal in the event, and Australia won the Silver Medal—coming second to England by only six seconds.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Other sports which were contested on the first day of competition included swimming and diving, weightlifting, shooting and bowls.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Sports contested included swimming, diving, weightlifting, shooting, cycling, bowls and archery.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The day was marred by both Australia and Canada being disqualified in the 4 × 100 metres relay in swimming, both problems occurring during change-overs.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The medals awarded for this race went to England, Scotland and New Zealand.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Sports contested included swimming, diving, cycling, athletics, archery, hammer throwing and shooting.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The day was marred when Canada was again disqualified, this time in the 4 × 200 metres freestyle relay.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Canada protested against the winners, Australia, as well as against their own disqualification.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] One of the targets of the protests was Queensland's *Aborigines Act 1971*, which restricted and controlled the lives of Aboriginal people in Queensland.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] There were large marches on 26 September (2,000 people), 20 September (1000), and a sit-in of 104 people on 4 October.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Also on that day, around 20 spectators held Aboriginal flags in the stadium during the entire program.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] On 7 October, about 500 people attended another protest, and 400 police arrested 260 people, including then Governor-General's daughter, Ann Stephen.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The protests were all peaceful, but police came out in force and blocked roads, making arrests under Queensland's *Traffic Act*.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Activists taking part in the protests included Gary Foley and Bob Weatherall (both leaders of the protest); Billy Craigie; Lyall Munro Jnr; Ross Watson; Wayne Wharton; and Selwyn Johnson and his family.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Selwyn's brother Hedley Johnson was a musician, of the Brisbane group Mop and the Dropouts.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Their song, "Brisbane Blacks", written by Mop Conlon, became a kind of anthem for the protests.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The protests, which were followed by large-scale arrests, are a significant event in the history of the Australian Aboriginal rights movement.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] When the Commonwealth Games returned to Australia in 2018 at the Gold Coast, it drew a series of peaceful protests.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] The documentary *Guniwaya Ngigu* also called *We Fight* (1982) follows the Aboriginal protest movement during the Commonwealth Games, and was directed by Madeline McGrady and Tracey Moffatt, and produced by Maureen Watson, Tiga Bayles and Madeline McGrady.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] In 2009 as part of the Q150 celebrations, the 1982 Commonwealth Games were announced as one of the Q150 Icons of Queensland for its role as a "Defining Moment".
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Brisbane also bid for the 1992 Summer Olympics but lost to Barcelona.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] Queensland Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk announced on 9 December 2019 that the state will make an official bid for the 2032 Summer Olympics and Paralympics featuring venues across Brisbane, Gold Coast and Sunshine Coast.
[src:1982-commonwealth-games/1982-commonwealth-games] In 2021, the city won the bid to host the 2032 Summer Olympics and Paralympics.
